fonline access with authorization2star  aUrban slum dwellers—especially in emerging-economy countries—are often poor, live in squalor, and suffer unnecessarily from disease, disability, premature death, and reduced life expectancy. Yet living in a city can and should be healthy. Slum Health exposes how and why slums can be unhealthy; reveals that not all slums are equal in terms of the hazards and health issues faced by residents; and suggests how slum dwellers, scientists, and social movements can come together to make slum life safer, more just, and healthier. Editors Jason Corburn and Lee Riley argue that valuing both new biologic and “street” science—professional and lay knowledge—is crucial for improving the well-being of the millions of urban poor living in slums.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and townsxHealth aspects. 0aSlumsxHealth aspects. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology). 0aUrban healthzBrazil. 0aUrban healthzIndia. 0aUrban healthzKenyazNairobi. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh1 aAgarwal, Siddharth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrade, Aurelio N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButala, Neel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorburn, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorburn, Jason, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDouglass-Jaime, Guillermo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelzemburgh, Ridalva D. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHavemann, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaranja, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKimani, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb